ons, this Greek name meaning 'sweetly speaking' maintains an old-world charm that few parents discover."]}],null,["$","li","14",{"className":"text-muted-foreground ml-4 mb-1 list-decimal","children":["",["$","strong","1",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"Aurelius"}]," — Only 9 babies received this imperial Roman name. While Marcus is common, Aurelius stands alone in its rarity."]}],null,["$","li","16",{"className":"text-muted-foreground ml-4 mb-1 list-decimal","children":["",["$","strong","1",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"Seraphina"}]," — Despite celebrity usage, only 7 babies received the full Seraphina (not Sera or Seraph). The name means 'fiery ones' from Hebrew."]}],null,["$","li","18",{"className":"text-muted-foreground ml-4 mb-1 list-decimal","children":["",["$","strong","1",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"Thessaly"}]," — A geographic name from Greece, given to just 5 babies. It combines place-name trends with classical appeal."]}],null,["$","li","20",{"className":"text-muted-foreground ml-4 mb-1 list-decimal","children":["",["$","strong","1",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"Octavian"}]," — With 8 registrations, this Roman emperor's name meaning 'eighth' remains virtually unknown among modern parents."]}]]}]
